During times we are “supposed to” “feel joy” it can feel especially jarring not to. While we know from holiday movies that this can be a tough time of year, it can still feel very lonely to feel like you’re the only one struggling. There are many reasons we may experience more struggle during the holidays (and your therapist being off duty doesn’t help). Just know you’re not alone if you’re feeling the intensity of the season. With all the pressure for joy, don’t forget to allow yourself to feel the rest of your feels for they are valid and welcome too.
•
Why many struggle with mental health during the holidays:
✨ The pressure to "feel joy" might mean we push down our authentic emotions, or experience guilt when we feel something other than joy.
✨ Family dynamics come to the forefront as we're often spending more time in close quarters with family.
✨ Overstimulation. With many plans and gatherings, we may be pushing ourselves through social events we don't have enough capacity for. Not to mention a lot more outside stimulus. This can be especially true for neurodivergent folks.
✨ When we see others gathering with loved ones, or have the expectation that we should be gathering with loved ones, our own lonliness may come to the forefront.
✨ Grief. This can show up in many ways. We can feel grief for those who are no longer with us. We may also feel grief for the younger parts of ourselves that awaken with the memories and wonder of the season.
✨ Feeling pressure to experience "holiday magic" that may feel unattainable.
✨ Emotions we might have compartmentalized or put to the side with work arise in its absence.
✨ We can't numb a single emotion without numbing them all and we can't feel one emotion without feeling them all. When we are able to access more joy, we might also access emotions that feel more difficult.

I would tell my younger-therapist self to let go of the guilt that I felt for taking time off when I got sick. As a therapist who deals with chronic illness, sometimes I need to reschedule sessions when I get sick suddenly. These days are always frustrating because often my mind is up to the task but my body isn't. Today is one of those days- I have severe asthma and chronic bronchitis and one of the side effects of this is that I lose my voice at least once a year. Though I spend a good portion of my sessions listening, I do still need to talk to do my job! 
I remember my first year out of grad school I got very sick around this same time that year. At the time, I knew a lot less about what was causing me to get sick so frequently, and how to care for myself when that happened. I was 23, and had just landed a job that I had been very hopeful about but was quickly realizing had a toxic workplace culture. I worked through my illness for a week even though I felt terrible, and finally took time off when my voice quit on me. I felt stressed and guilty about it the whole time.
Fast forward to today- I woke up with no voice after going to a friend's wedding over the weekend and singing my heart out to Taylor Swift at the reception. I woke up, realized I needed to rest my voice for another day, and emailed my clients to reschedule. I've spent the day catching up on emails, doing laundry, trying all the home brew laryngitis remedies recommended by my lovely coworkers, and writing this post. It is still frustrating to lose time to illness, but I don't feel the guilt that I used to feel. I have a supportive work environment and wonderful colleagues that encourage me to take care of myself. 
If I could tell my younger therapist self one thing, it would be that being a therapist doesn't mean you have to be super-human. You still get sick and you deserve to take the time you need to get well. Let go of the guilt and practice what you preach when it comes to self care!
•
Samantha Meyer, LPC

In an age where we are bombarded with information, it can feel like healing means knowing everything about ourselves. (TW: you may feel attacked) some of us even become therapists to get the knowledge we actually feel we need for our healing (not naming any names but hi it’s me I’m the problem it’s me). I’m not saying that information is a negative part of the healing process or that we don’t need it. It can help us make sense of our experience and find a commonality to know we are not the only person who is experiencing something. We can find relief in knowing something is actually a universal human experience or the experience of a sector of humans. AND knowing all the information is not the key to healing. It is what follows the knowing that is key. It is how we integrate and embody the information. It is how we put our healing in to practice.
•
Knowing my triggers and understanding how my brain works due to trauma is helpful. The reason it is helpful in an embodied way is because once I have that information, I can offer myself compassion when I’m triggered instead of thinking I’m bad or wrong. It can stop the shame that may cause my trigger to grow.
•
We can know journaling or moving our bodies is good for us but if we aren’t doing it, it is just knowledge. In the age of information, we don’t pause often enough to take it in. To notice where the information is landing in our bodies. To pay attention to what we want to do with it.
•
So next time you read something that resonates—pause. Notice what happens in your body. Notice the parts of you that are awakened. Notice what you want to do with the information.

As I’m preparing for our training this weekend, I was going back through Deb Dana’s work, “The Polyvagal Theory in Therapy.” I come back to books like this often because there is something new to be gained each time I return. As a clinician who breaks down stigma and shared knowledge around trauma, I wanted to share a nugget I hadn’t thought about in some time.
•
As trauma survivors, it can feel comforting to acknowledge our differences from those not impacted by trauma. That the way our trauma has impacted us has left an imprint so deep, our entire system has shifted in response to it even causing ‘symptoms’ or parts of us to form in response. Sometimes these acknowledgements can feel helpful while other times it may feel further stigmatizing.
•
As someone who has been deeply impacted by trauma in my own life, this piece of the Polyvagal theory that Deb Dana shared so simply and beautifully eased my own system. I want to share it with you in hopes maybe it will do the same.
•
Without going too far in the depths of Polyvagal theory (and yes I know some folks disregard it, for me it feels helpful as a way to conceptualize trauma), our ventral vagal system represents safety and connection. This part of our parasympathetic nervous system was evolutionarily the last to develop. This means, the systems that respond to threat are more primitive than the ventral vagal system. It is not just trauma survivors who are primed to respond to threat—all of us are. This means we are primed to assume threat FIRST. Once our system assesses for threat and recognizes safety, our ventral vagal system then comes online and we can activate play and connection.
•
As trauma survivors, we often live in a state of threat because we haven’t experienced the safety we needed so our threat response systems know they don’t have to work as hard. AND we can acknowledge that safety and connection are learned and ingrained. They are not our natural state. We assume threat until we learn otherwise and we can share in this human experience to normalize our own.
•
Resource: “The Polyvagal Theory in Therapy” by Deb Dana.

As we begin to acknowledge our trauma and the sacred stories we hold, as we begin to learn more about what happens inside of us in response to the trauma we endured, we may begin to wonder if we are fully taking in our reality or living through a trauma lens. As we perhaps begin to share our sacred stories with others, we may find that some people make us feel as though we are perceiving things through a trauma lens—being overly perceptive or overly cautious.
•
When we experience trauma, our system becomes hypersensitive to outside stimulus. Our systems begin to work in overdrive to keep ourselves safe. This can absolutely lead to a mis-perception of danger. If you’ve experienced anxiety, you know the feeling of your system misreading danger. However, this also makes us more alert to danger than the average person. We are more alert to a change in someone’s face or tone. We are more alert to what is happening around us. We are more alert to shifts in relationships—someone pulling away or moving too close. Trauma pushes us to live in a state of shutdown or hypervigilance. Danger becomes the assumption rather than safety. Chaos becomes the state we thrive in because our systems know how to move through it.
•
As trauma survivors, we can learn to wield our super powers. To trust our gut or intuition. To let those who don’t fully understand know it is not that we view the world through a trauma lens, it is that our bodies adapted to what we endured to better protect us in the future. Our sensitivities—our adaptations—are our strengths.

There are some things we have experienced that are too horrific to make meaning of. Too distressing for the level of distress to be a 1 or 0. Too big to fully tuck away. Maybe it’s something we need to hold on to because it includes pieces or people we hold dead. Maybe it’s something we need to hold on to so we don’t forget. So it doesn’t happen again. Healing doesn’t have to be a process of fully minimizing distress or fully tucking something away. It is not a process of never experiencing the difficult emotions again. Instead, it is a process of integration. Of putting the memories back where they need to be so our bodies don’t mistakenly believe we are reliving the thing. It is a process of putting the memories back together so they no longer live in fragments. A process of acknowledging how big the ‘thing’ was and is. Of making space for its bigness so it doesn’t take up so much space making itself known. 
There are some things that just won’t be fully healed, and we can make space and hold acceptance for that too.

When our outside circumstances are tough, parts of us get stirred that may be difficult to be with or explore. They can feel urgent when we’re in the muck but when the difficult thing has passed, suddenly those parts calm down. Things settle, go back to ‘normal’, we feel fine. That doesn’t means the parts go away or aren’t an issue any longer. It means they don’t need to come on as strongly to do their job because things are no longer on fire. Don’t forget to tend to those parts of you even when things are ‘okay.’ Don’t forget to sift through the muck even when life has settled. They don’t go away—they simply get buried deeper—drift from the surface because their job isn’t urgent.
•
The shit that gets stirred up when things are hard still needs to be worked on when things get easy again. It is so deserving of being worked on even when your world isn’t on fire. Don’t forget to tend to the parts of you that calm down when your chaos has calmed.

As a Jewish person, the experience of the Christmas season is new to me. It wasn’t until I was with my partner that I got to experience Christmas and it wasn’t until I had kids that I REALLY got to experience Christmas. As an outsider (and autistic person) there’s a lot I’ve noticed—from the sensory overwhelm of tradition and expectation to the pressure placed on it being magical. I have loved getting to experience the traditions I felt left out of as a kid AND it’s strengthened my appreciation for my family’s own traditions. There is the excitement of giving gifts, the build of anticipation, AND there is a lot of social expectation on how gifts are received. For neurodivergent folks, it can be a time of heavy masking. We feel the pressure of being on display, receiving gifts, and having to react to them even though getting more ‘stuff’ and potentially stuff we don’t want can be really overwhelming. We feel like we have to perform receiving the gift.
•
I feel the pressure build with the holiday season for it to be a magical time. There is childlike wonder but this can also awaken young parts of ourselves. There is anticipation and a management of disappointment. There is the juxtaposition of feeling like we’re supposed to be happy even if we’re not.
•
Give yourself permission for things to be in magical. Make space for the joy AND the discomfort. Make space for the magic AND the grief. It can also be magic to see the lights through tears in your eyes. Make space for that type of magic too.

We shouldn’t wait to talk about suicide until we lose someone, but in honor of tWitch, here’s what I want you to know: There has been a lot of rhetoric reminding folks to reach out to friends. 

I also want to remind you that they might not respond. They might respond and say they’re okay. They might respond with a joke.

Don’t stop reaching out. Connection is the biggest antidote to distress.

When someone dies by suicide it is not because you didn’t check in. 

It’s because the pain was too much and they saw an exit. It’s because there was access to means. It’s because we don’t have enough in place systemically to support people in the ways they need and deserve.

Short answer incoming for complex nuanced topic. As always this is my view and understanding of things.
•
My answer to why survivors of Complex PTSD seem to have a chronic sense of loneliness.
•
The simple answer is many of us didn’t have loving people to internalize growing up. Because caregivers couldn’t attune or offer safety we weren’t able to internalize loving safe people. As we grow up, we are able to tolerate being alone because we have people within our system who taught us to do-regulate, to feel in to safety, that even when we are alone we are never really ‘alone’ because we have an inner system of loving others we can pull from.
•
The good news? It’s never too late to build your system of loving others. Hold on to the inner experience of safety and community you receive. Notice how it lands within you. Notice what it lights up within your head and your heart. We are all capable of safety, or co-regulation, of moving away from loneliness.

In IFS (internal family systems) trainings we are put in to home groups. These groups are about 6 of us and a program assistant that we meet with throughout the training as a bookend to our weekends. My training was a year long, meeting once a month on long weekends. Our home group supported each other through the depths of the training—coming up against parts of us who didn’t feel confident about our therapeutic skills, parts of us that were stirred from past trauma or current hard things, and we also built up a real good banter. Since that training which started pre-Covid and ended about 2 months after lockdown, our home group decided to meet bi-weekly as a consult group. While we do a lot of consulting on our work as therapists, and a whole lot of banter too, we’ve also become a holding place for the tough stuff: the isolation of Covid, big losses and grief, the struggles of parenthood (new parenthood for me but even grand parenthood for others). They held me through the writing of this book and the subsequent release. There have been parts of me who wanted to shy away from letting them in on everything, who worried about putting ‘too much’ on them only to find their arms opened wider.
•
Someone in my home group recently had their car broken in to and the thief stole her copy of “The Tender Parts,” there was upset for the break in but then we laughed and wished the thief the best on their healing journey. That’s the kind of people they all are.
•
So this is an IFS home group appreciation post but also a pause to recognize how lucky I am to have safe people. How lucky I am to have a net behind me. To know that in writing this book, these were the people holding me up that allowed me to get my message to so many others.
•
If you have those people in your life I encourage you to pause often and take in the gratitude. And if you don’t yet, just know they’re out there.
•

As I’m wrapping up my year with one day of work left, I’ve been gently reflecting. When we take stock of our year in big ways it can feel disappointing or disheartening. Our brains can be more drawn to our shortcomings or what we are looking forward to doing NEXT. So much happens in a year. It goes far beyond big achievements or shortcomings. When I look back on my year of course I’ll remember the birth of my baby, the release of my book, the challenges in my relationship, the trip to Disney world. I also want to acknowledge the moment my daughter’s teacher congratulated me on my book because she’d been talking about it in school, the moment I first hit dinner made and felt peace with having 3 children, the moments I felt care from the people around me, the small moments of growth and healing with clients, the small moments of growth and healing within myself. There wasn’t as much space to slowdown but the moments I was able felt so very tender. I’m holding on to all of this tightly as I ease toward the end of this year. What are the moments you’re holding?
✨ What did slowing down look like this year?
✨ What were some moments of safety?
✨ What were some moments of play?
✨ When did you feel held or supported this year? By whom?
✨ What did healing look like this year? Where in your life does that work show up?
✨ What were some difficult moments you moved through this year?
✨ What were some moments of ease or softness?
✨ What made you proud (big or small)?
✨ What will you take with you in to the new year? What will you leave behind?

You may notice in the rush of hope, in moving toward the new and exciting or new and different—a sort of sadness arises. If you pause with it, the sadness may feel confusing. There is so much to look forward to and yet, there’s a sinking in your chest. Perhaps it’s not sadness, but a deeper feeling. One you’ve tried to push down. Perhaps, it’s grief. In growth and change, there is loss. In our biggest transitions, there is loss. Before we make room for the new parts of ourselves, there is loss of the old ones. As we integrate parts of ourselves, it can feel like we’re mourning them. When we don’t make space for the grief, when instead we move past it, it shows itself in ways we don’t expect. It can pull us in to its depths. When we pause to be with it, to welcome it even, we can befriend our grief instead of making it an enemy, numbing it out, making it take shape as something else (rage, depression, anxiety). So with the new, acknowledge the losses, whether they are people or places or parts of you. The grief can be beautiful and like any other part, is so deserving of your attention. So very deserving of your compassion.

This post is circulating as we approach the new year. Seemed time for a repost and a little update. ❤️ 
•
As the new year starts to creep in, the pressure of setting goals or resolutions may begin to arise. This has shifted in the wellness community to setting intentions rather than goals. I want to offer an even softer alternative of setting a theme. 
•
Goals and resolutions can be ableist and have become intrinsically linked to diet culture. Themes allow us a refresh without shame of where we’re at.
•
A theme is a word or phrase that represents your hope for your year or how you would like your year to look. This word can run through many aspects of your life, pushing you toward something ever so gently. It leaves room for growth and shifts but removes failure.
•
There is so much unknown as we tiptoe toward 2021. Leaning in to a theme rather than goals allows room for the great unknown.
•
My theme this year is making space for grief. There is so much grief rising to the surface within me as change approaches. Rather than pushing it down, I want to move toward it. To embrace the grief that shows up alongside the younger parts of me who are finally receiving the changes they needed long ago. To embrace the grief alongside the fear, the excitement, the sadness.
•

This phrase is said often, ‘let go of that which no longer serves you.’ We say it simply and expectantly. As if letting go is as simple as releasing your hand, or falling backwards knowing a safety net will be there. But letting go isn’t simple. Especially for those of us who formed many parts to help us survive.
•
For me letting go evokes free falling with no safety net beneath. Letting go evokes forced release. Letting go evokes leaving behind without pause to look back.
•
I remember watching a balloon being released in to the sky as a child. I did not marvel at its beauty, instead I worried about the sea turtles beneath who might choke when it inevitably falls in to the ocean.
•
Letting go with no acknowledgement of what we are leaving behind can be avoidance. 
•
When we talk about letting go, we aren’t talking about getting rid of the jeans you’re waiting to fit in to again. We’re talking about releasing the belief that you have to fit in to those jeans once again to be worthy. We’re talking about the parts of you that held on to this belief for protection. Perhaps that part of you believed love or acceptance was equated with body. This may be a part that no longer serves you as you move toward body acceptance—as you move toward body love—as you move toward enjoyment of food. But perhaps this part holds tightly to the feeling you got at 16 when your mom commented how great your body looked. When it was, perhaps the first time you felt noticed and praised by mom. To let go of this part of you would be leaving it alone. Would be making the part feel bad or wrong, when instead to unburden, perhaps it needs love in the form of grief. To make it feel seen as YOU did the day your mom noticed you.
•
Before we let ‘things’ go, we must acknowledge them as parts of ourselves that once served us. That once helped us survive. That once held on to beliefs so tightly because they believed those beliefs aligned with being loved. 
•
So before you let go, pause to acknowledge that part of you. To thank it for helping you survive. To let it know how you feel toward it. To embrace it. 
•
So know you don’t have to let go,  instead perhaps, you can move through, unburden.

To anyone whose looking at others highlight reels, to anyone watching the highlight reels go by and wondering why your year didn’t look like that, I want you to know the highlights aren’t always what they seem. On paper, in images, this was my best year. I had dreams come true this year. I had a baby. I wrote a book. And yet, on the final day of 2022, I look at the images and can’t stop thinking about how they don’t reflect the depth of difficulty of this year. In many ways I feel like I was broken apart and never able to put myself back together. So if your highlights reel doesn’t match your insides, if you don’t even have a highlight reel at all, I see you. I want you to know what was happening through my smile, through the highlights. Feeling as though at any moment my cracks would show through what my external facade tried so hard to hide. We can hold the highlights tightly and close to our hearts but make room for what’s beneath them. Here’s to more breaking apart in 2023 and filling the cracks with gold.

This was my little cottage on Douglas street in Echo Park when I was 22. If you’ve read my book, you know this 22 year old part of me holds deep significance. I get stuck in time with her often for she holds so much of my pain. So much happened at this little cottage. I got my dog, I was mugged and my best friend raced back from a video shoot in the desert to scoop me up, I got my heart broken, I fell in love, I recognized my trauma for the first time.
•
I’ve been coming in deep contact with this 22 year old in different ways during my trip as I’ve connected with the places that held her magic. This word has been coming up often for me as I’ve connected with her. That 22 year old saw magic in everyone around her. She was in awe of her friends and yet it feels like she didn’t squeeze tightly enough. She thought everyone else held magic but couldn’t see it in herself. Now I see it. Now I can scoop her up and let her know the magic she saw in everyone else, they saw in her too. The magic she saw in everyone else, I see in her too. The magic she saw in everyone else, she can see in herself now too.
•
Its both relieving and devastating that we can’t go back in time knowing what we know now. We can’t save our younger selves from the trauma they endured, the beliefs about ourselves the trauma created, or go backwards in time. We can connect with that part of ourselves in the present—whether we’re quite literally visiting our past or just accessing the younger parts we’ve pushed down.
•
That 22 year old shaped me in to who I am. She couldn’t see the magic but it was because of her that we lived the magic. I have so much tenderness for her. I have so much love for her. I see her magic—all of it.
•
I want her to know her loneliness and pain couldn’t be filled by anyone else. It wouldn’t be the love she so desperately hoped for that would heal her. I want her to know that with all the ways she tried to get away from herself—to numb and run and end her pain—now all I want is to be with her again, to be her again with all I know now.
•
And so I hold her magic up, so she can see what I see. So she can get unstuck from the past, safe inside her little cottage on Douglas. ❤️‍🩹

Going back to the place that held so much of my trauma and connecting with people who knew me in some of my most difficult days, allowed me to feel my growth. Out of our friend group, I would not have been the one that people thought, "yeah, she's going to get her life together and become a therapist." MAYBE a stand up comedian, MAYBE a music industry executive, but certainly not a therapist.
•
There is no silver lining that must come from trauma, and sometimes we go to our darkest places to emerge anew. As I spent time updating the younger parts of myself on where we are now: a mother, a therapist, an author, a human that goes beyond labels; I was able to be in delight with my present self. To acknowledge how far we'd come. To stand in awe of myself and the people who knew me at my darkest. To acknowledge we are alive, to acknowledge we are making the younger versions of ourselves proud.
•
When I decided to become a therapist, it wasn't because I reached the conclusion of my healing, it was because I was committed to it. It wasn't because I was above or past pain, it was because I could sit with my own pain in such a way that allowed me to sit with the pain of others.
•
Becoming a therapist means committing to your healing, your unfolding, your growth. It means recognizing we will be in relationship with people in such a way (clients and others) that our own *stuff* gets stirred and bumped up against. Rather than ignoring it, we commit to embracing it, to tending to it. It means recognizing the humanity we share--that I may fall as hard or fast as the next person. That my own brain and nervous system may betray me at any moment. That I may spend just as much time seeking answers as the next person.
•
Not all graduate programs require students to have experienced their own therapy before becoming therapists themselves. My own experience in therapy (good and bad) has been the biggest piece of my growth as a therapist myself. 
•
Many people joke when they find out someone is a therapist, "are you gonna psychoanalyze me or something?" When really, the only person I'm constantly analyzing and going to the depths with, is myself.

Reminder: it's okay to grow out of relationships as you grow in to yourself.
•
Sometimes we come in to relationship with the understanding and hope we will grow and change with someone. Sometimes we come in to relationship meeting each other just where we are at in the present with the understanding we are meeting in a place that satisfies a present need.
•
No matter how secure or comfortable you are with yourself, as humans we are meant to grow and change. Most of us are unable to stay stagnant. For some of us growth means further disconnection from self, while for others growth means coming further in to oneself. Those who tend to disconnect may adapt more easily to others, dimming ourselves to stay in relationship.
•
As we grow deeper in to ourselves, it may mean growing out of relationships. There can be immense grief as relationships end but it isn't always a bad thing. Sometimes we grow together, other times we grow apart. It signifies the normal course life takes.
•
The ability to know when to leave a relationship also signifies growth. It means we can acknowledge where we are in the present. We can recognize the relationship no longer feels right for where we are currently. We can lean in to the grief and discomfort that comes with letting a relationship grow. We can embrace the parts of us that may feel frantic facing the loneliness of a relationship's end. 
•
Perhaps a relationship has run its course, perhaps there is more conflict than joy, perhaps you are recognizing abusive facets, perhaps the relationship wasn't able to move toward the depths you'd hoped.
•
It's better to end the relationship than end your growth. It's better to end the relationship than shrinking to the old versions of you to keep it.

I’ve been thinking hard about how I make space for difficult things as a therapist. I don’t turn my therapist brain off when I leave the office, and I don’t leave my people behind. Instead, I like to think of it as creating pockets in my heart for each person I see. During the week they may pop out of my pocket as I think of them, and then I tuck them safely back in. It’s how I keep my own stuff separate from my work. It’s how I hold the heavy and tender things people share without just letting go of them. It’s how I carry the people I grow to care so very much about with me in a different way than I carry friends or family. If you’re a client, maybe this helps you to know that your therapist can hold all you bring to session. If you’re a therapist, maybe this can help you conceptualize how you can make space for all you hold and continue to hold on to it without letting it go.

There is so much grief to trudge through as I also move so much more deeply in to myself. It’s funny how sometimes the most difficult things can open us up to the version of ourselves we’ve been most waiting to meet. Connecting the younger parts of ourselves to this new version who is able to care for them so tenderly. Who is able to finally bring them to the present, away from the persistent trauma they were stuck in.
•
It is no easy decision to take a mental health break as a therapist and I also acknowledge the privilege in being able to do so. I recognized my own need for a break as my dissociative parts were taking over to numb the intensity of my experience outside the therapy room. As these parts took over, I realized I did not want them to take over in session—for my people to feel them and think they belonged to them, or worse, feel me drift out of connection with them. When intensity is happening outside the therapy room sometimes the most healing thing we can do for ourselves and our people is to take a step back.
•
So what did I do on my break? Therapy. Intentional dissociation to let those parts come through. Connected with friends. Spent time with my kids. Saw some music. Rekindled my love of music. Got settled in a new home. Spent time outside. Read for fun. Got wrapped up in scandoval (iykyk). Sandtray. Journaling. Moved more deeply in to myself. Met myself again and again. •

•
So I learned to push those parts of me down. To dim my light, to diminish my joy, to cease my delight.
•

But eventually I moved toward safety and those parts of me ignited once again. I found they were not lost at all, but buried. They learned to hide to dim our light, to slump our shoulders, to become small. To shrink so deep, I thought they no longer existed at all.

To feel the relief of connecting once again is a beautiful testament to the safety we are moving toward, are so deserving of, is attainable once again.
•
I'm relieved to know that all of me is still there, though fragments are piecing back together, part by part, discovering myself once again.

I am in a deep, intense period of grief. My distractor parts have been working hard to keep the grief at bay—to distract with friends and work and garbage television (sorry, the reality television arts). To distract with self care and new excitement. These distractors do a great job of burying my feelings. Pushing the uncomfortable down so we don’t have to touch the grief. These distractors know the big land mines that touch in to our grief, but they’re not prepared for the small, the mundane. We know the songs that will bring us to tears, the photos to keep hidden away, the subjects to avoid. We didn’t prepare for small things that lay adjacent to the grief. The bigger reminders that life has profoundly changed. That while I have younger parts of myself feeling so much relief, they are also feeling a lot of fear. When we intentionally touch in to the grief or uncomfortable emotions, it can feel more controlled. When it awakens seemingly out of nowhere, it can feel as though we will never move through it, like it’s intolerable, like we won’t reach the other side. I needed those moments of grieving hard and feeling the sadness. Of allowing all of my parts to grasp the gravity of our experience. Feeling deeply is also a reminder of my humanness. That growth comes with deep grief and pain. Yesterday was hard, today I feel lighter, tomorrow I don’t know what to expect and that’s okay.

I have always shown up here authentically. My posts are writings from my brain, my beliefs, what I’m processing. In sharing about my grief, I would joke to friends about coming across “unhinged” on my social media. As therapists we are supposed to be buttoned up, not let on when we’re going through our own shit. To be a therapist on social media is new territory. This is not just a space for ‘marketing,’ it has really become a space to share my writing and also my humanity—which is a part of desettling psychotherapy isn’t it? So I share with you that I’ve been struggling as a human. When I realized it was effecting how I showed up for my people I knew I needed to take a mental health break. When we go through big difficult things in our personal lives, we can’t expect them to remain completely separate from what happens in the therapy room. We show up as human and this means we show up with our full humanity. Keeping the outside world separate from what happens in the room takes practice, and even with great care and practice is not always possible depending on circumstances (we felt the immensity of this in the thick of COVID). I’ve been fully back for a week now and feel how much I needed my time away to rest and reset and learn to be in relationship with myself in new ways. Our care routines as therapists will be different for each of us, but I want to share the pieces that have supported me in my time of struggle as a human who is a therapist.
✨Therapy. Religiously. Weekly sometimes twice weekly.
✨Medication. It can be expected that when we are dealing with difficult things we may need to start or adjust meds.
✨Consultation with other professionals to assure I’m taking measures to support myself and show up for clients in a safe way.
✨Community. From a drag gram to seeing live music, my friends have shown the fuck up for me 😭.
✨Moving my body. I started aerial silks to build body trust and process my stuff.
✨Journaling with my parts.
✨Play. Being playful and free has been so healing.
✨Rest. In the ways my body allows. When I’m able.
•
I’m not unhinged. I’m healing and grieving and meeting parts of myself that lay dormant as new parts of myself develop.

When we experience overwhelm internally or externally—the nervous system has a beautiful way of aiding our survival and dimming the overwhelm, dissociation. Each of us has a natural baseline of dissociation though for some of us we experience it to an extreme which can be scary or confusing. In the midst of trauma, dissociation can disconnect us from our physical or mental pain so the experience is survivable. Dissociation feels different for different people but it is essentially a different form of consciousness. For some, dissociation can feel like a dream like state where we are lost in or disconnected from our thoughts. It can feel like a disconnection from brain and body, like floating above one’s body. It can feel like the world is not real. It can feel like you are not real. For some, dissociation can separate us in to different sectors of the brain, where our dissociative parts interact with the world for us. Dissociative parts can also hold certain memories we are protected from.
•
Life has been a lot lately. The news has been a lot lately. There is constant violence and devastation. I have also noticed a rise in heaviness in session as a therapist. So many of us have heavy things happening in our lives. If you hear the news and are unable to feel, perhaps it’s the mechanism of dissociation protecting you from the heaviness. If you are experiencing overwhelm in your own life and feel disconnected from it, perhaps you have dissociative parts protecting you from the overwhelm. It is not bad or wrong. It is not something we need to stop. Sometimes dissociation is just what we need to move through the overwhelm or terror of the day to day. We can hold the discomfort and scariness of experiencing dissociation AND honor the ways it has helped us survive.

What happens when you acknowledge the frustration? Does it allow your parts to move through the stuckness or does the stuckness grow stronger? It can feel scary to get to know those parts of ourselves because they can feel so intense and strong. What we often find when we get to know them better, when we check in with their hopes and fears, is these parts that keep us stuck are often afraid of losing us so they hold on tightly. 
•
As we move through phases of our life, it can feel as though we become different versions of ourselves. I consider this to be more of an unfolding—getting to know oneself better—moving deeper in to oneself. But the parts of us that have helped us function at different points in our lives fear that as we evolve we won’t need them anymore, so they hold on tightly, not wanting to lose us. To move through the stuckness we actually need to move through grief—our parts and ourselves. We actually need to acknowledge the fear that our parts hold—of losing us. We can assure them that as we evolve, we can still connect to the younger parts of ourselves and they can too. For we are not abandoning ourselves or our parts, we are evolving together.

So many of us are healing from hurt caused by others. Within this hurt, we often move in to a place of self blame—trauma survivors know this well. That the burden did not belong to us and we no longer have to carry it. To lean in to the love we ARE receiving to learn to turn it toward ourselves. To know that even when it feels lonely, and the loneliness is agonizing, we still have the capacity to turn love toward ourselves. I imagine a ring of light surrounding my heart, emanating to all parts of myself, as those parts take in my compassion, the scar tissue begins to slowly melt. We need to talk about a trend I’ve been seeing in my practice and in my life. There’s another type of emotional labor many women in cis heterosexual partnerships are experiencing—being the one healing within the relationship. I work with many mothers so I see this most often in motherhood but it happens often in child free relationships as well. 
•
When we become mothers we experience profound biological and psychological change to adapt to the survival of our children. This can push many of us in to therapy—especially if we experience perinatal mental health struggles such as postpartum depression. Most often we are not dealing only with the PPD on the surface, but confronting our past and our own childhood. In therapy, we also do a lot of work on parenting like learning how to regulate and show up best for our children. So often I hear (and have personally experienced) how lonely it can feel to be the healing one in a relationship that involves kids. Our healing helps us to show up imperfect but the best we can for our children. Because we are healing we can often better regulate and attune to our children, building a secure attachment relationship. This means our children may be more likely to come to us than a partner who is not working on their healing—thus the labor. Though we know healing is for US, the burden of being the healing partner can build resentment because it in turn has benefit for the family. In our healing, we become the regulating force not just for our children, but the family as a whole. 
•
There is further labor that comes along with this. As we build more awareness for ourselves, we build more awareness of what is going on with our partner and how therapy and healing could benefit them. In turn we may be the one trying to convince them to go to therapy, finding an individual or couples therapist, giving them reading material and so on and so forth. When only one partner is doing the emotional labor of healing—eventually we may also grow past our partner instead of growing together.
•
We can acknowledge the factors that often discourage cis het men from healing such as the stigma of going to therapy and lack of physiological changes.

I attended a grief retreat this weekend. And yes, I have parts that want to tell you it was some woo woo therapist shit. I have parts of me that laugh thinking about the experience but the laughter moves quickly from a place of judgement to delight. The grief retreat was a sacred space to be intentional about grieving. In our western culture we’ve been taught not to grieve too loudly. Not to take up space with our grief. Not to look too sad—or worse—angry, because it will make others uncomfortable. To move quickly through it then get back to normal life. To dissociate from it because we HAVE to get back to functioning in normal life. But when we leave grief unprocessed, it doesn’t go away. It sits in our bellies, in our chests, in our hearts, begging to be touched and held and noticed. It stays there until it’s touched and held and noticed. If it isn’t, it is passed on to the next generation once again begging to be touched and held and noticed. It shows up as anxiety, as depression, as ancestral trauma.
•
Our grief retreat was a sacred space. I cannot tell you exactly what it entailed. I cannot tell you how I was witnessed and how I witnessed others in their process. For the grief belongs in that sacred space to those who experienced it. I can tell you we grief cried. A wail that allows the grief to move viscerally through the body. I can tell you we were held and cared for in community. That we touched in to the deepest pain but also the deepest joys. That an intimacy, love, and safety was felt with each and every person in the group. A true connection of the heart. The process unfolded as it needed to and will continue to move through us.
•
And so, I continue to grieve.

•
If we recognize we are in a space of asking a partner to change rather than grow or in a space where we need growth within the relationship but our partner is unable to meet us there, we may need to acknowledge the relationship is not a fit.

We may hear ourselves say “you’ve changed so much” when really, what we are seeing is growth. We can meet our partners in their growth and they can meet us in ours, or we can recognize we’ve grown apart.
•
So are you asking your partner to grow or are you asking your partner to change? Growth is the space we can meet each other in, while change is a space we may never meet.

To struggle with your mental health, and especially to struggle with PTSD is agonizing. We wake each day hoping to feel better—to find the thing that helps us to feel better. We may enter the therapy room hoping THAT is the week we experience the breakthrough we needed most for healing.
•
When I first began taking private clients as a therapist, it felt like I needed to offer a quick fix. I felt the pressure of saying in consult calls “ya for some people it could be a few months, for others it could be a few years…” As I’ve grown as a therapist and learned more about trauma and interpersonal neurobiology, I understand why we must move slow. I also acknowledge we exist in a healthcare system that doesn’t offer much room to move slowly—to recognize when trauma has been so deeply embedded, healing is an unfolding process rather than a destination.
•
Trauma shifts us to an equilibrium of the world not being a safe place. The “feeling better” that most hope to get to is an equilibrium that the world IS a safe place or that we can exist in a sense of safety most of the time. Stephen Porges says it takes 10 sessions for most of our people to experience safety in the therapy room. Not because the therapist isn’t offering it, but because safety is a full nervous system experience and therapy involves being vulnerable with a stranger, establishing relationship, and connection.
•
Trauma causes our systems to be hyper sensitive to threat, so when the threat inevitably comes we can launch in to a threat response to assure the trauma doesn’t happen again. In trauma therapy, we are healing the stuckness of trauma so the traumatic material embeds correctly within the brain and nervous system. This is not just a shift in thought, but full nervous system healing. We are asking our nervous systems to orient to and live in a space of safety when, for so long, they have been oriented to danger. This coming in to safety can feel unsafe. When we move too fast in healing it can be dysregulating, making our nervous system go in to over drive to respond to threat.
•
So we move slow, because the therapist must earn the trust and experience of safety from the client. (Contd in caption)

When we enter in to trauma healing work, or contemplate entering in to trauma healing work, it can feel scary and uncertain. It's common that we fear opening something we will not be able to close. Trauma healing means accessing emotions and memories that may have been buried deep.
•
In parts work and Internal Family Systems, we move through trauma by moving toward the parts of ourselves that developed in response to the trauma. These parts are adaptations that helped us cope in some way. We experience them as embodied pieces of us. They can exist in body sensation, images, thoughts, and emotions. 
•
Because IFS and parts work is a modality used in trauma healing, it too can feel scary prior to experiencing it.
•
However, in parts work there is built in safety. Unlike other ways of working that may push past barriers to process trauma, in parts work we welcome each part that comes forward. This means when protectors show up, we don't move past them to get to our more vulnerable parts or inner children. Instead, we check in to see if the protectors would be willing to step to the side so we can continue getting to know the other parts. If the protectors won't step to the side, we don't continue on, making your system feel unsafe. Instead we pause to be with the protective part. We receive the messages. We understand. We make it feel heard. We thank it for doing its job.
•
We might be working with just protectors for a long time before getting to the deeper parts. We don't push past to get to the meat. We continue with the protectors until they determine it is safe enough, that we are ready enough, to proceed.
•
In this we honor our beautiful protective systems by listening and respecting the ways they attempt to keep us safe.

Last week my anxiety was intensified. I found my heartbeat racing, my thoughts ruminating, and it felt as though the world was both sped up and slowed down at the same time. I found myself fixating on things that didn’t actually matter much. Though I know these anxious parts well, when my anxious thoughts feel normal, sometimes it’s difficult to decipher them from just being normal thoughts. It wasn’t until a friend pointed out how anxious I sounded that I recognized it for what it was.
•
I’ve come to recognize our anxiety is often a shield for something deeper that we are unable to touch. It is the top layer of the onion. To make the anxious parts of ourselves calm, it is not the anxiety we must give in to or explore.
•
When I paused with my own anxiety I found grief beneath it. When brain fixated and ruminated on things that didn’t really matter, it made the things that DID matter shrink. It made them hurt less.
•
When I sent gratitude toward my anxious thoughts for keeping the pain at bay and asked them to step to the side, I was able to tend to the grief. We can hold both the discomfort of anxiety and gratitude for the ways it can show up in an attempt to help us function and to put our difficult emotions to the side until we are able to be with them.

Feeling the heaviness of anxiety or depression? When we’re feeling intense anxiety or depression, we tend to turn inwards and feel stuck. The feeling overwhelms us and we may experience a heaviness that feels difficult to release or get out of. It feels as though the depression or anxiety overtakes us. We tend to say “I’m depressed.” Or “I’m anxious.” Taking the anxiety or depression on as almost an identity.
•
In Internal Family Systems Therapy or parts work, we allow space from the overwhelming feeling by shifting the phrase to “a part of me is depressed” or “I have a depressed part of me.” This helps us identify that we are not our depression and we are not our anxiety (even though it might feel that way) it is simply a part of our internal experience.
•
What happens for you when you shift the phrasing? Do you notice more spaciousness inside? That the intensity of the feeling softens? What do you have more space for as the feeling softens?
•
When I understand these facets of myself as parts (and yes, even as a therapist I have my depressive and anxious eps), it allows me to connect with my depressive and anxious parts so they can feel seen and heard. We often think if we tend to these parts of us they will grow or stick around longer, but making more space for them and getting to know them actually allows us more ease and allows them to release more quickly.

A common experience we don’t often talk about as therapists is this feeling of not being ‘enough’ for our clients. Not having enough knowledge. Not having enough trainings or certifications under our belt. Not having enough experience. The thing is—this experience of feeling like not ‘enough’ doesn’t occur just for therapists who are new to the field (though we might feel it more intensely at the beginning of our careers) it happens for therapists who are 20 years in.
•
We feel this on multiple levels—one is systemic. Psychotherapy was built feeling less than but trying to live up to medical practice. The medical model was built to legitimize the practice of psychotherapy. We are also a field that is constantly learning and adjusting to new research which is wonderful. The thirst for learning is why many of us came to this field. This also builds on a capitalist mentality that you must have the latest and greatest trainings and certifications to stay relevant and support your clients.
•
Many of us as therapists also have old ideas about not being ‘enough’. My own stories around this come from past trauma and undiagnosed neurodivergence that left me working on overdrive through my schooling to meet my peers even half way.
•
Many of us sit alone with our experience of not enoughness, not wanting to appear unprofessional to our peers. When we give voice to it, we find that it actually comes from a deep care for our clients. Those parts of us are pushing us to excel because they believe they can shame us in to being the ‘best’ therapist. The truth is, there is no best therapist and there never will be. When we are gifted with spaces to share our vulnerabilities and insecurities in connection with other therapists who get it, we find at the heart of our work, the real healing factor, is our ability to connect with our clients in a human and authentic way. For this, we also need space to connect with other therapists in a human authentic way.

We all have an inner critic or critical parts of ourselves. It's the voice, or voices, inside that tell us we aren't good enough, we aren't doing it right, they don't like us. 
•
While some of us have a softer inner critic that pops in only occasionally, those of us who have experienced trauma may have louder and more intense inner critics. It might even feel like our critic takes over and we live our lives with the critic in control.
•
In response to the critic, we may find ourselves saying things such as "why am I so hard on myself?" We don't recognize these statements as being self critical as well.
•
When we look deeper and listen closely to our critics, we often find their voices and words don't sound like our own. Often, our inner critics are a collection of the people who have criticized us in the past. Our critics learned to shame us from those we were shamed by. 
•
Though our critics feel harsh, when we get to know them, we often find they are attempting to protect us. By shaming us to keep us in line, they are attempting to keep us from being shamed by others.
•
When we respond to our critics with further criticism, we are actually perpetuating this cycle of shame rather than breaking it. What might happen if instead we responded with curiosity and compassion? If we offered gratitude toward these parts of ourselves? While their attempts to protect us might hurt us, they are still attempts at protection. If we can offer gratitude and acknowledge these attempts, we can aid these parts of us in softening. Turning toward our inner critics with the compassion we aim to offer ourselves.

They must be felt, not skipped over.

Parts work, specifically Internal Family Systems has transformed my work as a therapist but has also seen me through personal transformation.
•

Parts work is a way of looking at the complexities of our internal world through the lens of having many parts. Have you ever heard yourself saying “a part of me wants to...” In this way of working in therapy and in thinking about our inner experience, we consider our adaptations, emotions, and  variations of self to be parts of our internal system with their own emotions, roles in the system, and connections to trauma endured. 
•
As a trauma survivor, I often got stuck in a pattern of black and white thinking. An adaptation to my trauma was viewing things as all one thing or all another, including myself. When I first heard the explanation that we have parts within us that function as entities and work to keep us safe and these parts mean that we are multifaceted—that trauma is not our sole identity but parts were formed in response to trauma—I felt immense relief. It meant what I had experienced was only a part of me and that I had many other parts of me too. And that the parts that formed in response to trauma actually didn’t make up self. I had a self that was formed separate from my trauma and it is something I can return to.
•
I’m so passionate about parts work and working this way with clients that I literally wrote the book on it—“The Tender Parts” is meant as an accessible way for folks to experience parts work through self lead readings and exploration.  I’m so excited to teach more therapists about this modality in my Intro to Parts Work training coming up next weekend! Link to both in my bio. 🪆

I’ve been trying to come through with a post here for some time. This space has often been one for my writing and thoughts and has often been one where I’m extremely transparent. The grief comes in waves, sometimes feeling so heavy I wish I didn’t feel it, then it lifts again and I feel the energy come through. It is taking the risk even though it could break your heart and pull you more deeply in to grieving. It is knowing that one day your energy for the *real* stuff will be there, but that day is not today. 
•
So I will feel the shame because I understand that part of me is trying to move me back toward the version of me I once was. And I will feel the grief that is pushing me toward the person I’m becoming.

•

I know I can still be vulnerable (and this is) while keeping much of this for me (and perhaps I'm living what will be my next book).
•
As someone who holds so much intergenerational trauma around doing and success, having to pull back was a jarring shift. As therapists, there are so many people in our work and personal lives who count on us to be their secure attachment figures. Where do we pull from when the well is empty and we no longer have a secure attachment figure ourselves? What do we do when our chosen careers depend on us showing up for others, even through our deep pain?
•
In my year of grief, I've experienced deep lows between immense moments of joy. I've scheduled meals with friends to make sure I nourish myself. I've said yes to trips. I've said yes to healing retreats and tried to back out but went anyway. I've shared my pain with others who have the capacity to hold me in it. I've done weekly therapy. Group therapy. Trainings that felt like therapy. I've laughed and cried at my healing journey. I've showed up when I could and knew when I couldn't. Happy re-birth day to me.

I went to Ireland to grieve. More concisely, I went to Ireland to participate in a grief ritual. As therapists, we cannot stop our work when our own lives feel as though they need to stop and our own grief and pain does not stop for our work. In this year of folding in to my own grief and pain I believe my humanness has made me more open and available to hold pain with others.
•
I’ve been absent here because I’ve been deeply tending to my own healing. Healing does not accelerate for us as therapists when we hit something intense but I know I need to tend more deeply to my own healing so my own stuff does not leak out in to my work with clients. In my own deep healing, I also hold grief for those who aren’t able to experience this because it is not accessible, it is too scary, it is just unknown.
•
So often we grieve alone—if at all—and in that the grief isn’t often fully moved through. You see grief lives in our bodies. We need to weep it, yell it, shake it, vomit it, move it out. We also need to be held and met in our grief rather than holding it alone, for when we hold it alone and unmet, we risk falling in to shame.
•
In our grief ritual, we spent 2 days grieving in community. Our grief represented on an altar in pictures and objects, donned with candles and leaves. One by one, and then several groups at once, we shared our stories of grief and pain and wept and drummed and primal screamed together. It wasn’t in my own story that my grief was unlocked though it held deep wells, it was in the shared stories. Hearing that others felt similar pain. That others endured what I had. It was in weeping together and literally and figuratively holding one another.
•
When we returning from our grieving states, the group would welcome us back in music and embraces. Our faces changed. When we finished weeping, there was a glow about us, our cheeks naturally rouged, each person seeming younger and changed. When I returned from my grieving I could feel the ground beneath my feet once again.
•
I faced my own grief bravely and intensely so I can more deeply and openly hold it for others.
•
And so I say to myself in this space and in the world, “welcome back.”

I've been transparent about this being a heavy year for me, but I am not alone in this. It has been a heavy year for those around me, too. 
•
As you can imagine, I am often in spaces with therapists and healers. When we endure pain or trauma as healers, many times we have parts of ourselves who arise that believe we are supposed to process the pain or trauma in the "right" way. We might even have parts who believe we aren't supposed to endure *that* particular thing. This is especially true of relational trauma--believing we should have known better than to enter the relationship or should have known to end it sooner.
•
We may hold beliefs around needing to "hold it together" as we grieve or move through or heal. 
•
And in this, we sometimes forget what we would tell our clients.
•
If you are a therapist or healer moving through your own pain, I want you to know (take what you need)...
•
"It was not your fault."
"You're allowed to fall apart."
"There is no 'right way' to process."
"You're not your own therapist."
"It's okay to take a break."
"You must tend to yourself before you can tend to others."
"I believe what happened to you."
"You couldn't have known better."
"That reaction did not come from you, it came from your threat response."
"All parts of you are welcome."
"All parts of you are deserving of love."
"You don't have to be okay all the time."
"Being human makes you a better therapist."
"Tell yourself what you would tell your clients."

Are you pausing to grieve when you see a father grasping his dead child for the last time? When you see mothers crying, begging to get their babies back? When you babies taking care of babies because the adults have been killed? Did you pause to grieve for the millions of people across the globe who died of COVID? For melting glaciers? To acknowledge the privilege of it not being you?
•
We are faced with unimaginable atrocities. We can not possibly conceive of how many people are dying currently in the Middle East and how many we lost and are losing to COVID. But when we look away and say “not me,” when we protect our own peace by not feeling the weight of the sorrow, we take away the humanity. It is the humanity we need to truly be activists. When we process grief, we make space to listen and acknowledge. We make space to feel. To create our own human impact. We see faces rather than numbers and graphics on phones. We understand there are people under the rubble and the rubble used to be homes.
•
So feel the sorrow. See the faces. Let out a guttural SCREAM. Feel the sorrow. Wail and sob and shake. Hold the hands of your community, look them in the face and wail and sob and shake together. We cannot even conceive of the magnitude of what we are witnessing. We will not make sense and have a full understanding. But we can know that no one should ever have to pull their child from the rubble of their crumbling home or stare in to a poster wondering if their babies will be returned alive.
•
So make space for grief and then fucking fight.

We lose our humanity when we place certain lives at higher value than others.
We lose our humanity when we cannot make space for nuance and grey area.
We lose our humanity when we forget to see the faces of real people.
We lose our humanity when we post blindly putting real lives at risk.
We lose our humanity when rage overtakes open heartedness.
We lose our humanity when we place blame on a people.
We lose our humanity when we believe mourning of any kind is propaganda.
We lose our humanity when we believe it is higher stakes for those of us not directly effected.
We loser our humanity when we argue rather than come together around a common love and care for humanity. 

Do not lose your humanity, we need it.

The truth as I’m moving toward looking back on my year. I didn’t grow my business or write another book. I didn’t start the podcast I’ve talked about forever. I didn’t exceed milestones I think I *should* have. I didn’t grow much on social media, in fact I kind of disappeared. I didn’t figure out any new and impressive marketing tactics. A part of me wants to look back and hold shame for not meeting myself where my past business minded self would have been proud. But she hadn’t gone through *it* yet.
•
I didn’t exceed my business expectations but I bravely attended two grief retreats. I showed up for weekly therapy authentically and vulnerably. I got back on antidepressants when I needed to. I participated in a year long IPNB training that caused me to enter in to new territory within my attachment system. I allowed myself to be fully present and feel all the feels as I cried at the Eras tour (twice) and Renaissance tour (once live, twice on film). I allowed friends and loved ones to hold me in my grief. I learned to reach out for support when I needed. I developed a sweet care team. I moved my body in new ways and learned to listen to it. I met new parts of myself and tended to the ones who felt neglected. I rescued my 22 year old part from within. Between the moments of deep grief I experienced ecstatic joy. I leaned in to new and old friendships and allowed people to meet and know me even in my pain.
•
It was my year of grief and healing.
•
So if you’re like me and looking back at your year and thinking “all I did was heal,” I want you to know we did a whole lot. ❤️‍🩹

Many of us don’t fully embrace our emotions out of fear. Fear we won’t return from feeling in to the discomfort—the sadness, the grief, the anger. We may fear that if we embrace the uncomfortable emotions, they will come out towards others. We would share too much or make them sad too or the anger would make us cause harm. The truth is, when we do horrible things, or dump on someone else, we are often disconnected from our emotions because we are dissociating rather than embracing them. When we don’t tend to our emotions, we pass them on to those around us. We ask future generations to carry them for us. They get stuck in our bodies and turn in to illness or deeper mental health struggles.
•
Being fully with our emotions allows us to move through them. It can feel like a lot to be IN it but the relief we feel when we come out the other side makes the embrace worth it. Being with our uncomfortable emotions allows space for us to feel the pleasant emotions too. To be more fully in joy. To be more fully in presence and connection.
•
Through this year I have come face to face with difficult emotions. It was scary. At first they presented as big shadowy parts of myself. When I inched closer and held the big shadowy parts and let myself cry, they shrunk. They created more space for me. Beneath them were little ones they were protecting from the bigness. So cry and yell in to the abyss and then look face to face at yourself in the mirror and say, “welcome back.”

Healing is a privilege but it is not the luxury we often treat it as. It is hard work. We pull the roots laid before before us and plant new seeds. We contend with our past while facing a future that is unknown. We learn to build trust within ourselves to soothe the anxiety of a future unknown.
•
Healing is sacred and healers are sacred. I've been thinking a lot about the people we allow access to us--especially through our healing. Healing is something that many are afraid of (it's okay if it feels scary to you). I've noticed there are people we come across in our healing and especially as healers, who seek to be in close proximity to us because of the work we are doing. For those who are sensitive and caring of humans, we may offer that proximity because we care. Because we want to believe the best in humans. Because we are learning to see the best in ourselves and so, we see the best and offer ourselves to others. 
•
Some people seek our energy and growth but are not willing or able to offer the same energy in return. You are not bad or wrong for not offering that energy. You are not bad or wrong for protecting your energy. You are not bad or wrong for outgrowing people, for setting boundaries, for standing strong in your worth. 
•
There are parts of me who believe that protecting our energy means not being 'kind.' There are parts of me who believe that naming our gifts makes us 'selfish' or 'boastful.' There are deeper parts of me who believe that we need to be liked and setting boundaries or protecting our energy means we may not be. Or worse, that if we protect our energy too fiercely, we won't be loved.
•
When we heal, we invest time, money, energy, and so much pain. Healing is courageous on every layer. When we allow our energy to be taken by those who cannot meet us where we are, we disrespect our own process. It subtracts from the investment we've made in ourselves. 
•
When you feel yourself putting energy toward something or someone who no longer serves you, take a moment to take stock of your healing. What have you invested in your healing? What updates can you give your parts on how far you've come?
•
I will honor the healer and healing in me.

To the parts of me holding shame— I see you. When we make significant leaps in our healing, we may look back at the parts of us who were acting from an ‘unhealed’ place. I can be with the shame parts. I can be with the parts of me I feel shame for. I can understand where they were coming from and what they were seeking when I acted or responded from those parts. Often, when I get close to them, I can see more clearly that they were coming from a place of not wanting to be alone. They felt scared and so, they reached for something outside of us. They sought to end the pain that comes with loneliness.
•
Instead of allowing my shame parts to take hold, I can respond to those parts with compassion. I can scoop them up and let them know they are not actually alone because I am with them. I can let them know the hard work we’ve been putting forth in our healing. I will let them know we don’t have to be pulled backwards. We can move forward from this new place, even though that may be scary too.
•
If you are feeling shame in your healing for the parts of you that acted from an unhealed place, what would it be like to hold those parts in compassion so you can acknowledge just how far you’ve come?

As I’ve been continuing to deepen my personal healing, I’ve been sitting with this idea we speak of often as therapists. “We can only take our clients as deep in their healing as we’ve gone ourselves.”
•
I am always hesitant to recommend something unless I’ve actually tried it and sometimes will explore different modalities so I can see how it might land for clients. Many of us come to healing work knowing we will be doing our own healing in the process but there is a difference between becoming a therapist in order to heal and becoming a therapist because of where we are in our healing process. When we do not continue to deepen our healing and we are holding heavy things with our clients that may bump up against our own ‘stuff’ we may cause great harm. This doesn’t mean we must always be in weekly therapy but it means we should be consistently looking inward and embracing what aids us in looking inward.
•
I’ve recognized that the biggest piece of taking clients only as deep as we’ve gone in our own work is that when we haven’t touched something within ourselves—when we haven’t met the deep parts of ourselves that may be encased in protective parts—that may be hiding close to shame—we may fear meeting those parts within our clients. We may fear going to those depths with our clients. Having been to the depths within myself and gotten to know those very deep parts. Being in a space where I can embrace them without fear and move past my own protectors, I know clients can also build the capacity to go to those depths. When we notice tender feelings or emotions arising, we often reach outside of ourselves. We may believe that finding something outside of ourselves will aid in our healing or quell the discomfort of the intense emotions. When we reach outside of ourselves, the diminishing feeling is only temporary. It is when we go deeper within ourselves that we experience the healing.
•
Reaching outside ourselves distracts from the parts of us that are seeking our attention. Often, those parts have felt lonely or abandoned before and when we turn away from them, they sink deeper in this pain.
•
It can be scary to move deeper within. When we hold trauma, even trauma we are unaware of, we typically have fearful parts arise. These too can be uncomfortable. Rather than turning away, what might it be like to embrace them? To begin to understand and get to know their fears. 
•
It can feel like these parts are disrupting us from going deeper. Rather, they are often attempting to protect us. Sometimes they protect us from touching in to what we are not yet ready for, while other times they protect us from pain that lives to deep.
•
When you find yourself looking outside of yourself, pause and notice if there is fear coming forward. Notice where it lands in your body. Notice any messages you receive from the fear. What is it afraid might happen if it stepped to the side and allowed you to touch in with those deeper parts? Notice and welcome.
•
And for the ones who reach outside of yourself--what are they seeking?
